9Ô∏è‚É£ Summary

We are building an AI-based system that automatically detects manipulated bank statements using image forensics and machine learning. The system analyzes PDFs and images, applies multiple forensic techniques, computes a calibrated risk score, and generates clear, explainable results. This solution can act as a reliable fraud detection layer for banks and fintech platforms.

14Ô∏è‚É£ Challenges & Limitations
Challenges
Forensic calibration:
Techniques like ELA and compression are sensitive and may show mild signals even in genuine documents created using Word, scanners, or re-exported PDFs.
False positives:
Distinguishing between benign document complexity and actual manipulation required careful threshold tuning.
Synthetic data constraints:
Synthetic datasets do not fully capture advanced real-world fraud techniques, which can affect ML generalization.
ELA variability:
ELA results depend on image resolution and PDF-to-image conversion quality.
ML confidence stability:
ML predictions may remain conservative in borderline cases and require calibration with forensic scores.
Limitations
Optimized mainly for bank statements
Performance may vary on low-quality scans
OCR accuracy depends on document clarity
15Ô∏è‚É£ Next Steps & Improvements
Future Enhancements
Expand dataset with more diverse and realistic synthetic samples
Improve forensic score normalization across document types
Add deep-learning-based tampering localization
Strengthen ML models using ensemble or CNN-based approaches
Enhance OCR-based semantic validation of transactions
Expose the system as an API for real-world banking integration


